Since 2007 there have been four spills with the average PM tenure lasting 2.14 years. The Liberals passed rules to require two-thirds majority to unseat a sitting PM. This makes a spill less likely and since Morrison has made it 63% of the way towards 1/1/2021 deadline I'm dropping my original baseline forecast by 20%. The other ways that Morrison can loose his job (defeated in parliament, death, retirement, etc.) all seem unlikely so I'm dropping by another 10%. These items seem to cover most of my "outside" view by comparing Morrison historically to other PMs. Next I will start incorporating some "inside view" perspectives.

Base rate: Since 3 December 2007 there have been six prime ministers, including the incumbent Scott Morrison [1]. 3 Dec 2007 - 16 February 2020 (today) is a total of 4458 days. 4458 days/5 changes in PM = average PM tenure of ~892 days. The incumbent Morrison has been in office for a total of 541 days (24 August 2018 - today) so far, and there are 320 days left in this question's time frame. If Morrison is still in office on 1 January 2021, he will have been in office for 861 days - just 31 days short of the average prior tenure length. The base rate implies that if today was 24 August 2018, Morrison would have just slightly under a 50% chance of ceasing to be PM before 1 January 2021. However, given that he has remained in office since 24 August 2018, the base rate will consider the # days left in this question's time frame and the average PM tenure: 320 days left in time frame / average tenure of 892 = final base rate of ~36%

Morrison led a change in the Liberal party rules last year that means a two-thirds majority party-room vote is now required to replace a PM who won an election (a real national one, not a party room one!).[1] This was in reaction to the ridiculous state of affairs where public opinion polls continually freaked out both major parties while in power, causing them to switch leaders mid-term (which required only a majority vote in the party room).

The fact remains that his main rival is far less popular than Morrison, and the Liberal Party have little appetite for changing the PM again. The act would be disastrous for them.
